# TiltyTable Arcade — Open Sauce

We are building a **fun physical interactive arcade game for Open Sauce** on
TiltyTable hardware: real servo-actuated tiles, LEDs, Stewart tilt, roller-ball
input, scored gauntlet/practice levels, and synthesized cabinet audio. The
`arcade/` stack ties game logic, hardware adapters, and the cabinet display
together.

## Lore & characters

The cabinet tells a light dungeon-escape story:

- **Tilty** — protagonist, escaping to reunite with **Tiltelle**
- **Ken Jennings** — advisor on the **left**; calm game-show host voice; **only**
  character who explains mechanics and how to play
- **Troll** — antagonist on the **right**; taunts Tilty, especially when the
  timer runs low

Dual dialogue panels (Ken left, Troll right) are required on game-state
screens. Copy should feel like a game dev wrote it — personality, world-building,
stakes — not dry system labels like "HAZARD TILE".

## Cabinet UI copy (hard requirement)

The 854×480 projector kiosk is player-facing — not a marketing page, product
demo, developer console, or hardware dashboard.

- Every visible word must help the player understand the current state or take
  the next action, **through lore-appropriate dialogue and short commands**.
- Use short commands, essential game rules, timer/score labels, and clear
  results — often voiced by Ken; Troll adds pressure, not instructions.
- Do not show implementation details, device paths, hardware jargon, developer
  terminology, future integrations, diagnostics, or calibration details.
- Do not add slogans, promotional claims, or helper copy that merely repeats an
  on-screen action without adding character or context.
- Use `TILTYTABLE` as the title unless the project establishes a real game name.
- Keep level instructions limited to the immediate mechanic; explain ball
  placement on the placement screen (Ken voice).
- Optimize every state for immediate legibility at 854×480 from cabinet
  viewing distance.
- Preserve the old-school arcade visual style; lore is welcome, decoration for
  its own sake is not.

## Debug overlay (booth calibration)

An optional **ball-cell debug chip** is allowed when Kinect tracking is active
(`integrations.tracking.enabled`) or when the URL includes `?debug=1`. It must:

- Use technical labels only (`BALL CELL`, cell key, confidence) — not lore copy.
- Sit in a corner (top-right) so it does not cover Ken/Troll dialogue panels.
- Stay hidden in pure simulation runs without Kinect unless `?debug=1` is set.

## Tile colors (LED calibration)

Level maps and UI tile previews use the calibrated palette:

| Role | Color |
|------|-------|
| Floor (inactive) | Gray `#567DBB` |
| Special (point tile) | Blue `#001FFF` |
| OFF | `#000000` |
| Pits/hazards | Red `#FF0000` |
| Walls | Green `#4DFF00` |
| Start | Cyan `#00FFFF` |
| End | Magenta `#680056` |
| Path/neutral floor | Shrek `#F49400` |
